                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;This is my favourite answer, because it&apos;s building a UUID as a 16-byte (128 bit) value, and not its serialized, nice to read form. It&apos;d be trivially easy to drop the string stuff and just set the correct bits of a random 128bit, which is all a uuidv4 needs to be. You could base64 it for shorter URLs, pass it back to some webassembly, store it in less memory space than as a string, make it a 4096-size buffer and put 256 uuids in it, store in a browser db, etc. Much better than having everything as a long, lowercase hex-encoded string from the start.&lt;/span&gt;

